<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:lang="en-US" xml:id="section-workshop-quadratics-zero-principle-and-square-root-method">
    <title>Solving quadratic equations: the zero-product property and the square root method</title>

    <exercises>
      <title>Written Examples</title>

      <exercise>
        <title>Solving quadratic equations using the zero-product property</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            When the product of two numbers is zero, at least one of the numbers in the product must be zero.  This is a property unique to zero; e.g., when two numbers multiply to, say, ten, not only is it not the case that one of the two numbers need be ten, the only restriction on the two numbers at all is that neither be zero.
          </p>
          <p>
            When solving an equation of form: <me>ab=0</me>, the next step in the process is to state:<me>a=0\text{  or  }b=0</me>.  We then soleve the two new equations separately and state our solutions, or solution set.  For example:
            <md>
              <mrow>(4x+7)(2x-9)=0</mrow>
            </md>
            <md>
              <mrow>4x+7\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x-9\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>4x\amp=-7\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x\amp=9</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=-\frac{7}{4}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=\frac{9}{2}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            The solutions are <m>-\frac{7}{4}</m> and <m>\frac{9}{2}</m>. The solution set is <m>\{-\frac{7}{4}, \frac{9}{2}\}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We frequently have to perform some preliminary steps before invoking the zero-product property.  Specifically:
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol label="1">
              <li>Completely expand both sides of the equation.</li>
              <li>Add and/or subtract to/from both sides of the equation so that one side of the equation is zero.  The next step will be easier if make sure that the second degree term (<m>ax^2</m>) has a positive coefficient.</li>
              <li>Factor the non-zero side of the equation.</li>
              <li>We are now set to invoke the zero-product property.</li>
            </ol>
            <p></p>
          </p>
          <p>
            Several examples follow.
          </p>

          <p>
            Example
            <md>
              <mrow>4x^2\amp=4x+15</mrow>
              <mrow>4x^2-4x-15\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>4x^2-10x+6x-15\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>2x(2x-5)+3(2x-5)\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>(2x-5)(2x+3)\amp=0</mrow>
            </md>
            <md>
              <mrow>2x-5\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x+3\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>2x\amp=5\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x\amp=-3</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=\frac{5}{2}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
            </md>
            <p>
              The solutions are <m>\frac{5}{2}</m> and <m>-\frac{3}{2}</m>. The solution set is <m>\{\frac{5}{2}, -\frac{3}{2}\}</m>.
            </p>
          </p>

          <p>
            Example
            <md>
              <mrow>(x+6)(x-2)\amp=-16</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2+4x-12\amp=-16</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2+4x+4\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>(x+2)(x+2)\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>x+2=0</mrow>
              <mrow>x=-2</mrow>
            </md>
            <p>
              The solution is <m>-2</m>. The solution set is <m>\{-2\}</m>.
            </p>
          </p>

         <p>
            Example
            <md>
              <mrow>(x+4)(4x-5)\amp=(7x+10)(3x-2)</mrow>
              <mrow>4x^2+11x-20\amp=21x^2+16x-20</mrow>
              <mrow>0\amp=17x^2+5x</mrow>
              <mrow>0\amp=x(17x+5)</mrow>
            </md>
            <md>
              <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 17x+5\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 17x\amp=-5</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-\frac{5}{17}</mrow>
            </md>
            <p>
              The solutions are <m>0</m> and <m>-\frac{5}{17}</m>. The solution set is <m>\{0, -\frac{5}{17}\}</m>.
            </p>
          </p>

          <p>
            Example
            <md>
              <mrow>2-x^2\amp=(2-x)^2</mrow>
              <mrow>2-x^2\amp=(2-x)(2-x)</mrow>
              <mrow>2-x^2\amp=4-4x+x^2</mrow>
              <mrow>0\amp=2x^2-4x+2</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{1}{2} \cdot 0\amp=\frac{1}{2} \cdot (2x^2-4x+2)</mrow>
              <mrow>0\amp=x^2-2x+1</mrow>
              <mrow>0\amp=(x-1)(x-1)</mrow>
              <mrow>x-1\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=1</mrow>
            </md>
            <p>
              The solution is <m>1</m>. The solution set is <m>\{1\}</m>.
            </p>
          </p>



        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <title>Solving quadratic equations using the square root method</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>k</m> is a positive number and <m>u^2=k</m>, then:<me>u=\sqrt{k}\text{ or } u=-\sqrt{k}</me>.  The latter set of equations is frequently abbreviate as <me>u= \pm \sqrt{k}</me> which is read aloud as "<m>u</m> is equal to plus or minus the square root of <m>k</m>."
          </p>
          <p>
            For example, if <m>x^2=64</m>, then <m>x= \pm \sqrt{64}</m> which, of course, simplifies to <m>x= \pm 8</m>.  So the original equation has two solutions: <m>-8</m> and <m>8</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Another example follows.
          </p>
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>(3x+5)^2\amp=16</mrow>
              <mrow>3x+5\amp=\pm \sqrt{16}</mrow>
              <mrow>3x+5\amp=\pm 4</mrow>
            </md>
            <md>
              <mrow>3x+5\amp=-4\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 3x+5\amp=4</mrow>
              <mrow>3x\amp=-9\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 3x\amp=-1</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=-3\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            The solutions are <m>-3</m> and <m>-\frac{1}{3}</m>.  The solution set is <m>\{-3, -\frac{1}{3}\}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We frequently have to do some preliminary work to have an equation of form <m>u^2=k</m>.  The process involves completing the square.  Completing the square entails adding a number to an expression of form <m>x^2+bx</m> so that the resultant trinomial factors into a perfect square.  The number that complete the square is always the square of half of <m>b</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            For example, the number that completes the square for <m>x^2+10x</m> is <m>5^2</m> which is <m>25</m>.  Note:
            <md>
              <mrow>x^2+10x+25\amp=(x+5)(x+5)</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=(x+5)^2</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            The steps followed when using the square root method are listed below.
            <p>
              <ol label="1">
                <li>Perform any and all manipulations so that the equation has the form <m>x^2+bx=c</m>.</li>
                <li>Complete the square by adding <m>\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^2</m>.  Note that to keep the equation in balance <m>\left(\frac{b}{2}\right)^2</m> also needs to be added to the other side of the equation.</li>
                <li>Factor the non-constant side of the equation.  The equation should now have form <m>u^2=k</m>.</li>
                <li>If the constant, <m>k</m>, is negative, then the equation has no solution.  If <m>k</m> is zero, then the equation has one solution which is determined by solving <m>u=0</m>.  Step 5 is written under the assumption that <m>k</m> is a positive number.</li>
                <li>Invoke the square root property, i.e. <m>u=\pm \sqrt{k}</m>.  If <m>k</m> is a perfect square, you need to write out and solve two equations.
                <me>u=-\sqrt{k}\text{ or }u=\sqrt{k}</me>.  If <m>k</m> is not a perfect square, you may solve for <m>u</m> maintaining the plus/minus sign.  Make sure to simplify the square root should it simplify.</li>
                <li>State your solutions and/or solution set.</li>
              </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
            </p>
            Several examples follow.
          </p>

          <p>
            Example
            <md>
              <mrow>x^2-6x-7\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2-6x\amp=7</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2-6x+9\amp=7+9</mrow>
              <mrow>(x-3)^2\amp=16</mrow>
              <mrow>x-3\amp=\pm \sqrt{16}</mrow>
              <mrow>x-3\amp=\pm 4</mrow>
            </md>
            <md>
              <mrow>x-3\amp=-4\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-3\amp=4</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=-1\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=7</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            The solutions are <m>-1</m> and <m>7</m>.  The solution set is <m>\{-1, 7\}</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Example
            <md>
              <mrow>(2x-1)(2x+1)\amp=7-32x</mrow>
              <mrow>4x^2-1\amp=7-32x</mrow>
              <mrow>4x^2+32x\amp=8</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{1}{4} \cdot (4x^2+32x)\amp=\frac{1}{4} \cdot 8</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2+8x\amp=2</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2+8x+16\amp=2+16</mrow>
              <mrow>(x+4)^2\amp=18</mrow>
              <mrow>x+4\amp=\pm \sqrt{18}</mrow>
              <mrow>x+4\amp=\pm 3\sqrt{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=-4\pm 3\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            The solutions are <m>-4-3\sqrt{2}</m> and <m>-4+3\sqrt{2}</m>.  
          </p>
          <p>
            The solutions set is <m>\{-4-3\sqrt{2}, -4+3\sqrt{2}\}</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Example
            <md>
              <mrow>x^2+9x+25\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2+9x\amp=-25</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2+9x+\frac{81}{4}\amp=-25+\frac{81}{4}</mrow>
              <mrow>\left(x+\frac{9}{2}\right)^2\amp=-\frac{19}{4}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            The equation has no real number solutions.
          </p>
          <p>
            Over the real numbers, the solution set is <m>\emptyset</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Example
            <md>
              <mrow>4x^2-28x\amp=-11</mrow>
              <mrow>\frac{1}{4} \cdot (4x^2-28x)\amp=\frac{1}{4} \cdot -11</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2-7x\amp=-\frac{11}{4}</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2-7x+\frac{49}{4}\amp=-\frac{11}{4}+\frac{49}{4}</mrow>
              <mrow>\left(x-\frac{7}{2}\right)^2\amp=\frac{38}{4}</mrow>
              <mrow>x-\frac{7}{2}\amp=\pm \sqrt{\frac{38}{4}}</mrow>
              <mrow>x-\frac{7}{2}\amp=\pm \frac{\sqrt{38}}{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=\frac{7}{2} \pm \frac{\sqrt{38}}{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=\frac{7 \pm \sqrt{38}}{2}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            The solutions are <m>\frac{7-\sqrt{38}}{2}</m> and <m>\frac{7+\sqrt{38}}{2}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            The solution set is <m>\{\frac{7-\sqrt{38}}{2}, \frac{7+\sqrt{38}}{2}\}</m>.
          </p>




        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <title>Application problems involving quadratic equations</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Example
          </p>
          <p>
            You may be familiar with the Pythagorean Theorem:  If the legs of a right triangle have lengths of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> while the hypotenuse has a length of <m>c</m>, then <me>a^2+b^2=c^2</me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Suppose that we have a right triangle where one leg is <m>1</m> inch longer than the other leg and the hypotenuse is <m>1</m> inch longer than the longer leg.  Let's determine the length of each side of the triangle.
          </p>
          <p>
            Let <m>x</m> represent the length (in) of the shorter leg of the triangle.  Then the length (in) of the longer leg is represented by <m>x+1</m> and the length (in) of the hypotenuse is represented by <m>x+2</m>. 
          </p>

          <figure xml:id="Pythagereon-example-square-root-method">
                                <caption>Variable Diagram</caption>
                                <image width="60%">
                                    <description></description>
                                        <latex-image>
                                            <![CDATA[
                                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                                    \coordinate (A) at (0,3);
                                                    \coordinate (B) at (0,0);
                                                    \coordinate (C) at (4,0);
                                                    \draw (A)--(B)--(C)--cycle;
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$x$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$x+1$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[sloped](C,A){$x+2$}
                                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle(A,B,C)

                                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                            ]]>
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>

          <p> 
            Applying the Pythagorean Theorem we have <me>x^2+(x+1)^2=(x+2)^2</me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We begin solving the equation by expanding all expressions in the equation.
            <md>
              <mrow>x^2+(x+1)^2\amp=(x+2)^2</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2+x^2+2x+1\amp=x^2+4x+4</mrow>
              <mrow>2x^2+2x+1\amp=x^2+4x+4</mrow>
              <mrow>x^2-2x-3\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>(x-3)(x+1)\amp=0</mrow>
            </md>
            <md>
              <mrow>x-3\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+1\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=3\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-1</mrow>
            </md>
            Since a length cannot be negative, we reject the negative solution.  So the lengths of the triangle are <m>3</m> inches, <m>4</m> inches, and <m>5</m> inches.
          </p>
          <p>
            Example
          </p>
          <p>
            The area formula for a trapezoid is <me>\text{Area}=\frac{1}{2}(b_1+b_2)h</me> where <m>b_1</m> and <m>b_2</m> are the lengths of the parallel sides of the trapezoid (called bases) and <m>h</m> is the perpendicular length between the two bases (called the height). 
          </p>

                            <figure xml:id="trapezoid-example-square-root-method" width="50%">
                                <caption>A Trapezoid</caption>
                                <image width="60%">
                                    <description></description>
                                        <latex-image>
                                            <![CDATA[
                                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                                    \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                                                    \coordinate (B) at (6,0);
                                                    \coordinate (C) at (5,3);
                                                    \coordinate (D) at (2,3);
                                                    \coordinate (E) at (2,0);
                                                    \draw (A)--(B)--(C)--(D)--cycle;
                                                    \draw[dashed] (D)--(E);
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,A){$b_2$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[above](C,D){$b_1$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[right](D,E){$h$}

                                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                            ]]>
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>

          <p>
            Suppose that we have a trapezoid where the length of one of the bases is twice the length of the other base and the height is five inches shorter than the longer base.  Suppose further that the area of the trapezoid is <m>132</m> <m>\text{in}^2</m>.  Let's determine the length of each of the bases and the height.
          </p>
          <p>
            Let's define <m>x</m> to be the length (in) of the shorter base.  Then the length (in) of the longer base is represented by <m>2x</m> and the length (in) of the height is represented by <m>2x-5</m>.  
          </p>

                            <figure xml:id="trapezoid-example-variable-diagram-square-root-method" width="50%">
                                <caption>Variable diagram</caption>
                                <image width="60%">
                                    <description></description>
                                        <latex-image>
                                            <![CDATA[
                                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                                    \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                                                    \coordinate (B) at (6,0);
                                                    \coordinate (C) at (5,3);
                                                    \coordinate (D) at (2,3);
                                                    \coordinate (E) at (2,0);
                                                    \draw (A)--(B)--(C)--(D)--cycle;
                                                    \draw[dashed] (D)--(E);
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,A){$b_2=2x$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[above](C,D){$b_1=x$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[right](D,E){$h=2x-5$}

                                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                            ]]>
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>

          <p>
            Using the area formula for a trapezoid we have:
            <me>\frac{1}{2}(x+2x)(2x-5)=132</me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We begin solving the equation by clearing the fraction and expanding the left side of the equation.
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{1}{2}(x+2x)(2x-5)\amp=132</mrow>
              <mrow>2 \cdot \frac{1}{2}(3x)(2x-5)\amp=2 \cdot 132</mrow>
              <mrow>(3x)(2x-5)\amp=264</mrow>
              <mrow>6x^2-15x\amp=264</mrow>
              <mrow>6x^2-15x-264\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>3(2x^2-5x-88)\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>3(2x^2-16x+11x-88)\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>3[2x(x-8)+11(x-8)]\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>3(x-8)(2x+11)\amp=0</mrow>
            </md>
            <md>
              <mrow>x-8\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x+11\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=8\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x\amp=-11</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=8\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-\frac{11}{2}</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            Since length cannot be negative, we reject the negative solution. So the lengths of the two bases are <m>8</m> inches and <m>16</m> inches while the length of the height is <m>11</m> inches.
          </p>
          <p>
            Example
          </p>
          <p>
            If an object is dropped from a height (feet) of <m>h</m>, then the distance between the object and the ground after <m>t</m> seconds can be approximated by the function <m>f(t)=-16t^2+h</m>.  Let's use this information to approximate the amount of time it takes an object to reach the ground after being dropped from a height of <m>500</m> feet.
          </p>
          <p>
            Our distance function is <m>f(t)=-16t^2+500</m>.  When the object reaches the ground the value of <m>f</m> is <m>0</m>.  So the equation we need to solve is <me>-16t^2-500=0</me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            We can quickly determine the solution by isolating <m>t^2</m> and employing the square root method.
            <md>
              <mrow>-16t^2-500\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>-16t^2\amp=-500</mrow>
              <mrow>t^2\amp=\frac{125}{4}</mrow>
              <mrow>t\amp=\pm \sqrt{\frac{125}{4}}</mrow>
              <mrow>t\amp=\pm \frac{5\sqrt{5}}{2}</mrow>
            </md>
            Since the object cannot reach the ground before its been released, we reject the negative solution.  Using a calculator we have:
            <me>\frac{5\sqrt{5}}{2}\approx 5.59</me>.  So it takes about 5.59 seconds for the object to reach the ground after its release.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

  </exercises>

  <exercises>
      <title>Practice Exercises</title>

    <exercise>
        <title>Solving quadratic equations using the zero-product property</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the zero-product property to solve each quadratic equation.
            <ol>
              <li><m>(3x+8)(5x-7)=0</m></li>
              <li><m>x(x-6)=0</m></li>
              <li><m>x(x-3)=10</m></li>
              <li><m>x^2+12x=-36</m></li>
              <li><m>4t(8t+9)=5</m></li>
              <li><m>2y^2=y</m></li>
              <li><m>(w-10)(w+1)=-10</m></li>
            </ol>
            <p>
            </p>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We begin by setting each of the factors from the left side of the equation equal to zero.
                <md>
                  <mrow>(3x+8)(5x-7)\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                  <mrow>3x+8\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 5x-7\amp= 0</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x\amp=-8 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 5x\amp=7</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=-\frac{8}{3} \amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=\frac{7}{5}</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>-\frac{8}{3}</m> and <m>\frac{7}{5}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solution set is <m>\{-\frac{8}{3}, \frac{7}{5}\}</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We begin by setting each of the factors from the left side of the equation equal to zero.
                <md>
                  <mrow>x(x-6)\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                  <mrow>x\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-6\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=6</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>0</m> and <m>6</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solution set is <m>\{0, 6\}</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We begin by making the right side of the equation zero and then factoring the left side of the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>x(x-3)\amp=10</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2-3x-10\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>(x-5)(x+2)\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                  <mrow>x-5\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=5 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-2</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>5</m> and <m>-2</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solution set is <m>\{5, -2\}</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We begin by making the right side of the equation zero and then factoring the left side of the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>x^2+12x\amp=-36</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2+12x+36\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>(x+6)(x+6)\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>x+6\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=-6</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solution is <m>-6</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solution set is <m>\{-6\}</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We begin by expanding the left side of the equation, making the right side of the equation zero, and then factoring the left side of the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>4t(8t+9)\amp=5</mrow>
                  <mrow>32t^2+36t\amp=5</mrow>
                  <mrow>32t^2+36t-5\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>32t^2+40t-4t-5\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>8t(4t+5)-1 \cdot (4t+5)\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>(4t+5)(8t-1)\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                  <mrow>4t+5\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 8t-1\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>4t\amp=-5 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 8t\amp=1</mrow>
                  <mrow>t\amp=-\frac{5}{4} \amp\amp\text{ or }\amp t\amp=\frac{1}{8}</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>-\frac{5}{4}</m> and <m>\frac{1}{8}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solution set is <m>\{-\frac{5}{4}, \frac{1}{8}\}</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We begin by making the right side of the equation zero and then factoring the left side of the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>2y^2\amp=y</mrow>
                  <mrow>2y^2-y\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>y(2y-1)\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                  <mrow>y\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2y-1\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>y\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp y\amp=\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>0</m> and <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solution set is <m>\{0, \frac{1}{2}\}</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We begin by expanding the left side of the equation, making the right side of the equation zero, and then factoring the left side of the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>(w-10)(w+1)\amp=-10</mrow>
                  <mrow>w^2-9w-10\amp=-10</mrow>
                  <mrow>w^2-9w\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>w(w-9)\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                  <mrow>w\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp w-9\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>w\amp=0 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp w\amp=9</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>0</m> and <m>9</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solution set is <m>\{0, 9\}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <title>Solving quadratic equations using the square root method</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the square root method to solve each of the following quadratic equations.  Make sure that all solutions are completely simplified.  Stae both the solutions to the equation as well as the solution set for the equation.
            <ol>
              <li><m>(2t-1)^2=9</m></li>
              <li><m>(3x-2)^2=72</m></li>
              <li><m>x^2-8x+16=12</m></li>
              <li><m>y^2+20y+80=0</m></li>
              <li><m>x^2+4x+7=0</m></li>
              <li><m>w^2-7w+7=0</m></li>
            </ol>
            <p>
            </p>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol>

              <li>
                <p>We start by applying the square root property.
                  <md>
                    <mrow>(2t-1)^2\amp=9</mrow>
                    <mrow>2t-1\amp=\pm \sqrt{9}</mrow>
                    <mrow>2t-1\amp=\pm 3</mrow>
                  </md>
                  <md>
                    <mrow>2t-1\amp =-3\amp\amp\text{ or }\amp 2t-1\amp=3</mrow>
                    <mrow>2t\amp =-2\amp\amp\text{ or }\amp 2t\amp=4</mrow>
                    <mrow>t\amp =-1\amp\amp\text{ or }\amp t\amp=2</mrow>
                  </md>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    The solutions are <m>-1</m> and <m>2</m>.  
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    The solution set is <m>\{-1, 2\}</m>.
                  </p>
                  <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>We start by applying the square root property.
                <md>
                  <mrow>(3x-2)^2\amp=72</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x-2\amp=\pm \sqrt{72}</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x-2\amp=\pm \sqrt{36 \cdot 2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x-2\amp=\pm 6\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x\amp=2\pm 6\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{2\pm 6\sqrt{2}}{3}</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>\frac{2-6\sqrt{3}}{3}</m> and <m>\frac{2+6\sqrt{2}}{3}</m>. 
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solution set is <m>\{\frac{2-6\sqrt{3}}{3}, \frac{2+6\sqrt{2}}{3}\}</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                    We start by factoring the perfect-square trinomial <m>x^2-8x+16</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>x^2-8x+16\amp=12</mrow>
                  <mrow>(x-4)^2\amp=12</mrow>
                  <mrow>x-4\amp=\pm \sqrt{12}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x-4\amp=\pm \sqrt{4 \cdot 3}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x-4\amp=\pm 2\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=4\pm 2\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>4-2\sqrt{3}</m> and <m>4+2\sqrt{3}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>  
                  The solution set is <m>\{4-2\sqrt{3}, 4+2\sqrt{3}\}</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We start by moving the constant term to the right side of the equation and then completing the square on the left side of the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>y^2+20y+80\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>y^2+20y\amp=-80</mrow>
                  <mrow>y^2+20y+100\amp=-80+100</mrow>
                  <mrow>(y+10)^2\amp=20</mrow>
                  <mrow>y+10\amp=\pm \sqrt{20}</mrow>
                  <mrow>y+10\amp=\pm \sqrt{4 \cdot 5}</mrow>
                  <mrow>y+10\amp=\pm 2\sqrt{5}</mrow>
                  <mrow>y\amp=-10\pm 2\sqrt{5}</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>-10-2\sqrt{5}</m> and <m>-10+2\sqrt{5}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>  
                  The solution set is <m>\{10-2\sqrt{5}, -10+2\sqrt{5}\}</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>We start by moving the constant term to the right side of the equation and then completing the square on the left side of the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>x^2+4x+7\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2+4x\amp=-7</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2+4x+4\amp=-7+4</mrow>
                  <mrow>(x+2)^2\amp=-3</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The equation <m>x^2+4x+7</m> has no real number solutions.
                </p>
                <p>  
                  Over the real numbers the solutions set is <m>\emptyset</m>.
                </p>
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  We start by moving the constant term to the right side of the equation and then completing the square on the left side of the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>w^2-7w+7\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>w^2-7w\amp=-7</mrow>
                  <mrow>w^2-7w+\frac{49}{4}\amp=-7+\frac{49}{4}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\left(w-\frac{7}{2}\right)^2\amp=\frac{21}{4}</mrow>
                  <mrow>w-\frac{7}{2}\amp=\pm \sqrt{\frac{21}{4}}</mrow>
                  <mrow>w-\frac{7}{2}\amp=\pm \frac{\sqrt{21}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>w\amp=\frac{7}{2}\pm \frac{\sqrt{21}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>w\amp=\frac{7\pm \sqrt{21}}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                  The solutions are <m>\frac{7-\sqrt{21}}{2}</m> and <m>\frac{7+\sqrt{21}}{2}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>  
                  The solution set is <m>\{\frac{7-\sqrt{21}}{2}, \frac{7+\sqrt{21}}{2}\}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>

      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <title>Application problems involving quadratic equations</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>

              <li>
               A bean bag is shot into the air from the top of a 168 ft building with an initial upward velocity of <m>88</m> ft/s.  It can shown (using calculus) that the height (ft) of the bag relative to the ground is given by the function <m>h(t)=-16t^2+88t+168</m> where <m>t</m> is the number of seconds that have elapsed since the bean bag was released.  Determine the amount of time it takes for the bean bag to reach the ground upon its release.
               <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                One square inside another, with a <m>2</m> meter gap between the walls of the smaller square and larger square.  The area of the larger square is <m>484 \text{m}^2</m>.  Determine the perimeter of the smaller square.
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                One leg of a right triangle is <m>7</m> cm longer than the other and the hypotenuse of the triangle is <m>1</m> cm longer than the longer leg of the triangle.  Determine the length of each side of the triangle.
                <me></me>
              </li>

            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol>

              <li>
                We need to determine when the value of <m>h(t)</m> is equal to zero.
                <md>
                  <mrow>h(t)\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>-16t^2+88t+168\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>-\frac{1}{8} \cdot (-16t^2+88t+168)\amp=-\frac{1}{8} \cdot 0</mrow>
                  <mrow>2t^2-11t-21\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>2t^2-14t+3t-21\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>2t(t-7)+3(t-7)\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>(t-7)(2t+3)\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>t=7\text{ or }t\amp=-3/2</mrow>
                </md>
                Since the bean bag can't reach the ground before it is shot, we reject the negative solution.  So we see that it takes seven seconds from release before the bean bag hits the ground.
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                Let <m>x</m> represent the length (m) of each of the sides of the smaller square.  Then the length (m) of each side of the larger square is <m>x+4</m> (there are two additional meters of length on both sides of the smaller square).  

                <figure xml:id="square-in-square-exercise-square-root-method" width="50%">
                                <caption>A square inside square</caption>
                                <image width="60%">
                                    <description></description>
                                        <latex-image>
                                            <![CDATA[
                                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                                    \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                                                    \coordinate (B) at (0,8);
                                                    \coordinate (C) at (8,8);
                                                    \coordinate (D) at (8,0);
                                                    \coordinate (E) at (2,2);
                                                    \coordinate (F) at (2,6);
                                                    \coordinate (G) at (6,6);
                                                    \coordinate (H) at (6,2);
                                                    \coordinate (I) at (4.2,0);
                                                    \coordinate (J) at (4.2,2);
                                                    \coordinate (K) at (4.2,6);
                                                    \coordinate (L) at (4.2,8);
                                                    \draw (A)--(B)--(C)--(D)--cycle;
                                                    \draw (E)--(F)--(G)--(H)--cycle;
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[right](B,A){$\leftarrow 2$ m $\rightarrow$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[sloped](I,J){$\leftarrow 2$ m $\rightarrow$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[sloped](K,L){$\leftarrow 2$ m $\rightarrow$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[left](C,D){$\leftarrow 2$ m $\rightarrow$}

                                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                            ]]>
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>






                We are given that the area of the larger square is <m>484\text{ m}^2</m> which gives us the following:
                <md>
                  <mrow>(x+4)^2\amp=484</mrow>
                  <mrow>x+4\amp=\pm \sqrt{484}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x+4\amp=\pm 22</mrow>
                  <mrow>x=-4\amp\pm 22</mrow>
                </md> 
                Since the length of a side cannot be negative, we reject the negative solution.  So the smaller square has sides of length <m>18</m> m and its area is <m>324\text{ m}^2</m>.
                <me></me>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                 Let <m>x</m> represent the length (cm) of the shorter leg of the triangle.  Then <m>x+7</m> represents the length of the longer leg and <m>x+8</m> represents the length of the hypotenuse. <me></me>
                </p>

                    <figure xml:id="Pythagereon-exercise-square-root-method">
                                <caption>Variable Diagram</caption>
                                <image width="80%">
                                    <description></description>
                                        <latex-image>
                                            <![CDATA[
                                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                                    \coordinate (A) at (0,1);
                                                    \coordinate (B) at (0,0);
                                                    \coordinate (C) at (7,0);
                                                    \draw (A)--(B)--(C)--cycle;
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[left](B,A){$x$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[below](B,C){$x+7$}
                                                    \tkzLabelSegment[sloped](C,A){$x+8$}
                                                    \tkzMarkRightAngle(A,B,C)

                                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                            ]]>
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>

                <p>
                Using the Pythagorean Theorem and solving for <m>x</m> we get the following:
                <md>
                  <mrow>x^2+(x+7)^2\amp=(x+8)^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2+x^2+14x+49\amp=x^2+16x+64</mrow>
                  <mrow>2x^2+14x+49\amp=x^2+16x+64</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2-2x-15\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>(x-5)(x+3)\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>x=5\text{ or }x\amp=-3</mrow>
                </md>
                Since a length can't be negative, we reject the negative solution.  So the shorter leg of the triangle has a length of <m>5</m> cm and the lengths of the other two sides are <m>12</m> cm and <m>13</m> cm.
              </p>
              </li>

            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

